Let $w = z^2$.  Then
\[w^4 + (4 \sqrt{3} + 6) w^2 - (4 \sqrt{3} + 7) = 0.\]By the quadratic formula,
\[w^2 = \frac{-(4 \sqrt{3} + 6) \pm \sqrt{(4 \sqrt{3} + 6)^2 + 4(4 \sqrt{3} + 7)}}{2} = -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} \pm 2 \sqrt{3 + 2 \sqrt{3}}.\]Let $a = \sqrt{3 + 2 \sqrt{3}}.$  Then
\[w^2 = -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} \pm 2a.\]Hence,
\[w = \pm \sqrt{-3 - 2 \sqrt{3} + 2a}, \quad \pm \sqrt{-3 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2a}.\]We can write
\begin{align*}
-3 - 2 \sqrt{3} + 2a &= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} + 2 \sqrt{3 + 2 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} + 2 \sqrt{(\sqrt{3} + 1)^2} \\
&= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} + 2 \sqrt{3} + 2 \\
&= -1,
\end{align*}and
\begin{align*}
-3 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2a &= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2 \sqrt{3 + 2 \sqrt{3}} \\
&= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2 \sqrt{(\sqrt{3} + 1)^2} \\
&= -3 - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2 \sqrt{3} - 2 \\
&= -5 - 4 \sqrt{3}.
\end{align*}Thus, the roots of $w^4 + (4 \sqrt{3} + 6) w^2 - (4 \sqrt{3} + 7) = 0$ are $w = \pm i, \pm \sqrt{-5 - 4 \sqrt{3}}.$

Since $z^2 = w,$ the roots of $P(z) = 0$ are
\[z = \pm 1, \pm i, \pm \sqrt[4]{-5 - 4 \sqrt{3}}, \pm i \sqrt[4]{-5 - 4 \sqrt{3}}.\]We can write
\[\sqrt[4]{-5 - 4 \sqrt{3}} = \sqrt[4]{(1 - 2 \sqrt{3})^2} = \sqrt{1 - 2 \sqrt{3}}.\]Let $b = \sqrt{1 - 2 \sqrt{3}}.$  Then the roots of $P(z) = 0$ are
\[z = \pm 1, \pm i, \pm b, \pm ib.\]These roots form a regular octagon, as shown below:

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  return (dir(45*t));
}

path foo = moo(0)--moo(1)--moo(2)--moo(3)--moo(4)--moo(5)--moo(6)--moo(7)--cycle;

draw(foo);
draw(Circle((0,0),1));

label("$1$", moo(0), dir(0));
label("$i$", moo(1), dir(90));
label("$-1$", moo(2), dir(180));
label("$-i$", moo(3), dir(270));
label("$b$", moo(4), dir(45));
label("$ib$", moo(5), dir(135));
label("$-b$", moo(6), dir(225));
label("$-ib$", moo(7), dir(315));
[/asy]

The side length of this octagon is $2b,$ so the perimeter is $16b = \boxed{16 \sqrt{1 - 2 \sqrt{3}}}.$

